{{Short description|Shinto shrine in Taiwan}}
{{Draft topics|east-asia}}
{{AfC topic|geo}}

{{draft}}
[[File:At the Tainan Jinja.jpg|thumb|The shrine in the 20th century]]
{{ill|{{PAGENAME}}|ja|台南神社}} was a [[Shinto shrine]] made outside of [[Japan]] by the [[Empire of Japan]], or one that was planned on being constructed by the Empire. It is no longer active. It was linked to imperialism and [[State Shinto]] rather than local support for [[Shintoism]]<ref name=":0">{{Cite journal |last=Michio |first=Nakajima |last2=𠀓𤚇𙥷𡌕𰀇 |date=2010 |title=Shinto Deities that Crossed the Sea: Japan's "Overseas Shrines," 1868 to 1945 |url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/27822898 |journal=Japanese Journal of Religious Studies |volume=37 |issue=1 |pages=21–46 |issn=0304-1042}}</ref> It was established in 1920 and upgraded in 1925 and its main deity was [[Prince Kitashirakawa Yoshihisa|Prince Kitashirakawa]].<ref name=":0" />who died during the [[Japanese invasion of Taiwan (1895)|Japanese invasion of Taiwan]].<ref>{{Cite book |last=Operations |first=United States Office of the Chief of Naval |url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=YOcdAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA61&lpg=PA61&dq=Tainan+jinja&source=bl&ots=D1vKXI0qVZ&sig=ACfU3U230knJfb9T1j68RZfuLnds-Omd7Q&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjYl8z7_Jj-AhUkITQIHba1Btg4MhDoAXoECAIQAw#v=onepage&q=Tainan%20jinja&f=false |title=Taiwan (Formosa).: Tainan Province |date=1944 |publisher=Office of the Chief of Naval Operations, Navy Department |language=en}}</ref>

