{{ill|{{PAGENAME}}|ja|台南神社}} was a [[Shinto shrine]] made outside of [[Japan]] by the [[Empire of Japan]], or one that was planned on being constructed by the Empire. It is no longer active. It was linked to imperialism and [[State Shinto]] rather than local support for [[Shintoism]]<ref name=":0">{{Cite journal |last=Michio |first=Nakajima |last2=𠀓𤚇𙥷𡌕𰀇 |date=2010 |title=Shinto Deities that Crossed the Sea: Japan's "Overseas Shrines," 1868 to 1945 |url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/27822898 |journal=Japanese Journal of Religious Studies |volume=37 |issue=1 |pages=21–46 |issn=0304-1042}}</ref> It was established in 1920 and upgraded in 1925 and its main deity was [[Prince Kitashirakawa Yoshihisa|Prince Kitashirakawa]].<ref name=":0" /><ref name=":1" /> who died during the [[Japanese invasion of Taiwan (1895)|Japanese invasion of Taiwan]].<ref name=":1">{{Cite book |last=Operations |first=United States Office of the Chief of Naval |url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=YOcdAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA61&lpg=PA61&dq=Tainan+jinja&source=bl&ots=D1vKXI0qVZ&sig=ACfU3U230knJfb9T1j68RZfuLnds-Omd7Q&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjYl8z7_Jj-AhUkITQIHba1Btg4MhDoAXoECAIQAw#v=onepage&q=Tainan%20jinja&f=false |title=Taiwan (Formosa).: Tainan Province |date=1944 |publisher=Office of the Chief of Naval Operations, Navy Department |language=en}}</ref> from [[malaria]].<ref>{{cite news |author1=Han Cheung |date=26 May 2019 |title=Taiwan in Time: The prince who became a god |work=Taipei Times |url=http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/feat/archives/2019/05/26/2003715796}}</ref> He was enshrined in most shrines in Taiwan including [[Taiwan Grand Shrine]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=2019-05-26 |title=Taiwan in Time: The prince who became a god - Taipei Times |url=https://www.taipeitimes.com/News/feat/archives/2019/05/26/2003715796 |access-date=2023-04-08 |website=www.taipeitimes.com}}</ref>

