{{Infobox Shinto shrine
| native_name           = 台南神社
| religious_affiliation = shinto
| image                 = At the Tainan Jinja.jpg
| deity                 = [[Prince Kitashirakawa Yoshihisa]]
| consecration_year     = 1920
}}'''Tainan Shrine''' ({{Lang-ja|台南神社|translit=tainan jinja}}) was a [[Shinto shrine]] made outside of [[Japan]] by the [[Empire of Japan]]. It was linked to imperialism and [[State Shinto]] rather than local support for [[Shintoism]]<ref name=":0">{{Cite journal |last=Nakajima |first=Michio |last2= |date=2010 |title=Shinto Deities that Crossed the Sea: Japan's "Overseas Shrines," 1868 to 1945 |url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/27822898 |journal=Japanese Journal of Religious Studies |volume=37 |issue=1 |pages=21–46 |issn=0304-1042}}</ref>{{rp|30}} It was established in 1920 and upgraded in 1925 and its main deity was [[Prince Kitashirakawa Yoshihisa|Prince Kitashirakawa]].<ref name=":0" />{{rp|38}}<ref name=":1" /> who died during the [[Japanese invasion of Taiwan (1895)|Japanese invasion of Taiwan]].<ref name=":1">{{Cite book |last=Operations |first=United States Office of the Chief of Naval |url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=YOcdAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA61&lpg=PA61&dq=Tainan+jinja&source=bl&ots=D1vKXI0qVZ&sig=ACfU3U230knJfb9T1j68RZfuLnds-Omd7Q&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjYl8z7_Jj-AhUkITQIHba1Btg4MhDoAXoECAIQAw#v=onepage&q=Tainan%20jinja&f=false |title=Taiwan (Formosa).: Tainan Province |date=1944 |publisher=Office of the Chief of Naval Operations, Navy Department |language=en}}</ref> from [[malaria]].<ref name=":2">{{cite news |author1=Han Cheung |date=26 May 2019 |title=Taiwan in Time: The prince who became a god |work=Taipei Times |url=http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/feat/archives/2019/05/26/2003715796}}</ref> He was enshrined in most shrines in Taiwan including [[Taiwan Grand Shrine]].<ref name=":2" />

People were forced to visit shrines at this time by the government rather than going of their own volition.<ref name=":0" />{{rp|38}} It held an elaborate festival every January.<ref name=":1" />

It was converted into the Tainan [[Hero shrine|Martyr's shrine]] after the war alongside many other Shinto shrines in Taiwan<ref>{{Cite web |title=Chronicles of the Brave --National Revolutionary Martyrs' Shrine |url=http://library.taiwanschoolnet.org/gsh2006/gsh4337/index2/index2.html |access-date=2023-04-08 |website=library.taiwanschoolnet.org}}</ref>{{Better source needed|reason=The current source is insufficiently reliable ([[WP:NOTRS]]).|date=April 2023}}

